    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix uninitialized memory access in USER API notification handlers\n\n### Summary\nThe USER API notification handlers were accessing uninitialized fields in the `at_response_t` structures, leading to unpredictable behavior when sending AT command responses to the user application layer. This was particularly noticeable when handling PDN connection notifications where the response encoding would sometimes produce garbled output or cause the application to crash.\n\nThis fix ensures all `at_response_t` structures are properly zero-initialized before use.\n\n### Changes\n- `openair3/NAS/UE/API/USER/user_api.c`: Added `memset()` calls to initialize `at_response_t` structures in all handler functions:\n  - `_user_api_pdn_connection_handler`\n  - `_user_api_registration_handler` \n  - `_user_api_location_handler`\n  - `_user_api_network_handler`\n\n### Reproduction\nTo reproduce the issue:\n1. Configure UE to connect to a network with multiple PDN connections\n2. Monitor AT command responses from the user API interface\n3. Observe intermittent garbled +CGEV responses or segmentation faults when PDN notifications are processed\n4. Run with memory debugging tools to detect uninitialized memory reads in the AT response encoding functions\n\nThe issue occurs because local `at_response_t` structures contained stack garbage that would occasionally cause the string formatting functions to read from invalid memory addresses or produce incorrect output strings.\n"
}